sec.p:
The second modification consists of extension of the BHE arterial cannula using a length of knitted polyester graft (Vascutek Gelseal, Terumo, Tokyo, Japan). A graft with a diameter of 2 to 3 mm wider than the arterial cannula is used. When using a 6-mm BHE arterial cannula, we attach an 8-mm graft with five interrupted 5/0 polypropylene sutures through the sewing cuff. The metal flange of the 6-mm cannula allows a silk ligature to be passed around the graft to tie the conduit to the metal flange. For the 9-mm cannula, which does not have a flange, we use a 14-mm Vascutek graft that is joined to the cannula with a continuous 4/0 polypropylene suture reinforced as needed by a number of interrupted sutures. The graft is trimmed to a length of approximately 1.5 cm as needed and joined to the aorta (or pulmonary artery for right VAD [RVAD]). This anastomosis is easily performed after the application of a side-biting clamp using continuous 4/0 or 5/0 polypropylene (Figures 3
–5
). We apply tissue fibrin sealant to the anastomosis routinely before removing the side-biting clamp and leave the pleurae intact bilaterally where possible to avoid the need for postoperative pleural drainage.
